    "id": "c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8",
    "title": "Ghana's cocoa farmers embrace climate-smart agriculture to combat changing weather patterns",
    "originalUrl": "https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/ghana-cocoa-climate-smart-agriculture",
    "originalDescription": "Innovative farming techniques help Ghanaian cocoa producers adapt to climate change while maintaining world-leading chocolate production.",
    "description": "In the lush forests of Ghana's Ashanti region, traditional cocoa farmers are embracing revolutionary climate-smart agricultural techniques that promise to safeguard the world's second-largest cocoa production while adapting to increasingly unpredictable weather patterns that threaten the livelihoods of over 800,000 farming families and the global chocolate industry worth $150 billion annually. The comprehensive transformation program, supported by international development organizations and major chocolate manufacturers, introduces drought-resistant cocoa varieties, sophisticated irrigation systems, and innovative shade-tree management practices that maintain soil fertility while protecting cocoa plants from extreme temperatures and erratic rainfall that have become increasingly common due to climate change. Farmer cooperatives across the Western, Central, and Eastern regions are reporting remarkable results from these new approaches, with many experiencing 25-40% increases in yield per hectare while simultaneously reducing their environmental footprint through decreased pesticide use, improved water conservation, and enhanced biodiversity preservation through strategic intercropping with native tree species. The program addresses multiple challenges simultaneously: climate adaptation, poverty reduction, environmental conservation, and supply chain sustainability, representing a holistic approach to agricultural development that could serve as a model for other crop-dependent economies facing similar climate pressures. Kofi Asante, a third-generation cocoa farmer from Kumasi, explains how the new techniques have transformed his 15-hectare farm from a struggling operation barely providing subsistence income to a thriving business that supports his extended family while producing premium-quality cocoa beans that command higher prices in international markets. The economic implications extend far beyond individual farms, as Ghana's cocoa industry employs nearly 20% of the country's workforce and generates approximately $2 billion in annual export revenues, making climate adaptation crucial for national economic stability and the welfare of millions of citizens whose livelihoods depend directly or indirectly on cocoa production. International chocolate companies including Nestlé, Mars, and Hershey have committed over $500 million to support the climate-smart agriculture initiative, recognizing that long-term sustainability of their supply chains depends on helping cocoa farmers successfully adapt to environmental challenges while maintaining the quality and quantity of production that global chocolate demand requires.",
    "image": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/976/cpsprodpb/e5f6/live/ghana-cocoa-farmer-plantation.jpg",
