    "id": "d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9",
    "title": "Nigeria's Nollywood industry partners with Netflix for $150 million film production deal",
    "originalUrl": "https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/nigeria-nollywood-netflix-partnership",
    "originalDescription": "Historic agreement will fund 50 new Nigerian films and series, bringing African stories to global streaming audience.",
    "description": "Nigeria's Nollywood film industry has secured its most significant international partnership to date with Netflix announcing a groundbreaking $150 million investment deal that will fund the production of 50 high-quality Nigerian films and television series over the next three years, marking a transformative moment for African cinema and storytelling on the global stage. This unprecedented commitment represents Netflix's largest single investment in African content production and signals the streaming giant's recognition of Nollywood's immense creative potential and the growing international appetite for authentic African narratives that challenge Western-dominated entertainment industry perspectives. The partnership will support both established filmmakers and emerging talent, with specific provisions for female directors, writers, and producers who have historically faced barriers in the traditionally male-dominated industry, while also investing in state-of-the-art production facilities, training programs, and technical infrastructure that will elevate Nigerian cinema to international standards. Kunle Afolayan, one of Nigeria's most celebrated directors, describes the deal as 'a game-changer that will allow us to tell our stories with the resources and global reach they deserve,' while Netflix's African content director emphasizes the streaming service's commitment to authentic storytelling that reflects the diversity, complexity, and richness of contemporary African experiences. The economic impact extends far beyond the entertainment sector, with economists projecting that the Netflix investment could create over 10,000 direct and indirect jobs in Lagos's rapidly expanding film industry, from actors and directors to camera operators, sound engineers, costume designers, and post-production specialists who support the complex ecosystem of modern film production. Nollywood already ranks as the world's second-largest film industry by volume, producing over 2,500 movies annually and generating approximately $6.4 billion in revenue while employing over one million people across Nigeria's creative economy, figures that are expected to grow substantially as international partnerships provide greater resources and global distribution channels. The collaboration also addresses technical challenges that have limited Nollywood's international reach, including access to advanced filming equipment, professional sound recording facilities, and sophisticated post-production capabilities that are essential for creating content that meets global streaming standards while maintaining the authentic African aesthetic and storytelling traditions that make Nigerian cinema distinctive.",
