    "id": "a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2",
    "title": "Mali's ancient manuscripts digitization project preserves 700,000 historical documents",
    "originalUrl": "https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/mali-manuscripts-digitization-project",
    "originalDescription": "International collaboration saves priceless medieval African texts from deterioration and makes them accessible worldwide.",
    "description": "An ambitious international digitization project has successfully preserved over 700,000 ancient manuscripts from Mali's historic libraries in Timbuktu and other medieval centers of learning, creating the world's largest digital archive of African historical documents and making centuries of invaluable knowledge accessible to researchers, students, and scholars worldwide while protecting irreplaceable cultural heritage from environmental damage and political instability. The comprehensive preservation effort, coordinated by UNESCO in partnership with major universities and technology companies, utilized state-of-the-art scanning equipment specially designed to handle fragile manuscripts dating from the 12th to 18th centuries, many written in Arabic, local African languages, and hybrid scripts that document sophisticated intellectual traditions in mathematics, astronomy, medicine, philosophy, and Islamic jurisprudence that flourished in West Africa during the medieval period. These manuscripts, collectively known as the Timbuktu manuscripts, represent one of the world's most significant collections of historical documents from Africa, providing detailed insights into complex societies, international trade networks, educational systems, and cultural exchanges that challenge colonial-era narratives about African intellectual achievements and demonstrate the continent's central role in global knowledge production during the medieval era. Dr. Abdel Kader Haidara, director of the Mamma Haidara Commemorative Library, explains that many manuscripts were hidden by families for generations to protect them from various threats, and the digitization project represents the first time this knowledge has been systematically cataloged and made available to international researchers. The technical challenges were immense, requiring specialized equipment that could safely scan documents written on various materials including paper, parchment, and leather, many of which were severely damaged by age, humidity, and in some cases conflict-related destruction during recent political instability in northern Mali. The digital archive has already yielded remarkable discoveries, including previously unknown mathematical treatises, detailed astronomical observations, medical texts describing surgical procedures, and extensive correspondence between medieval African scholars and their counterparts in Cairo, Baghdad, and Cordoba that reveals the international scope of intellectual exchange centered in Timbuktu. The project's completion represents not only cultural preservation but also educational transformation, as the digitized manuscripts are now being integrated into university curricula worldwide, allowing students to study primary sources that provide authentic African perspectives on medieval history, science, and philosophy rather than relying solely on European interpretations of African civilizations.",
    "image": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/976/cpsprodpb/c0d1/live/timbuktu-ancient-manuscripts-library.jpg",
